<font color="#FF0000">POST-WAR GENERATION IN AMERICA</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr  7 16:06:17 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am 31 years old and also part of the post-war generation.  My earliest memory of the Vietnam war was watching my mother run over to our clunky stereo and turn up the news bulletin to hear the words 'Cease Fire.'  At the time I didn't know what that meant but it iginited in me an interest in Vietnam that has persisted since then. I grew up in the silened aftermath of the war and this just made me want to understand more, from the point of view of those who had fought in the war and from  the perspective of those Vietnamese who came to the United States after the war.<br><br>
I know the Vietnam war has had a lasting impact on all.  I am currently a film student at Stanford University working on a film about this piece of history from both the Vietnamese-American and American point of view.  I am especially interested in talking with people from the post-war generation.  If you are    interested in talking or know anyone who is please pass along this information.   Thanks.
<p><code>-- LKA@Leland.Stanford.edu  (Laura K. Almo) </code><p>


